en’s rooms, and twenty-first-century uproar over laws like North Carolina’s “bathroom bill,” Davis reveals how public restrooms are far from marginal or unimportant social spaces. Instead, they are—and always have been—consequential sites in which ideology, institutions, and inequality collide.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPublic toiletsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aRestroomsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aSex rolezUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069041540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520971660?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520971660423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520971660/original  a978-3-11-069041-5  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070474-7  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishb2020  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2020  aZDB-23-DKUb2020